  "chartNotes": {
    "rel_ppscat": "Flipper length vs bill length by species, with box-plot margins on each axis. The signature Palmer Penguins scatter; toggle Marginals in the controls.",
    "rel_ppheat": "Correlation heatmap (Pearson r) among the four body measurements for the visible rows.",
    "rel_ppsplom": "Scatter matrix: every pairwise relationship among the four measurements at once. Move the mouse over a point and see details of that point. From this graph, we can already see a certain linear relation between Body Mass and Flipper Length. Let's dig into this relationship in the next graph.",
    "rel_pppar": "Parallel coordinates across the four measurements. Drag along any axis to brush and filter the threads live.",
    "rel_pp3d": "3D scatter of bill length, bill depth and flipper length. Drag to rotate, scroll to zoom; the species sit in separate regions.",
    "dist_ppbox": "Body mass distribution per species (box plot with mean).",
    "dist_ppviol": "Body mass by species, split by sex (violin). Shows species differences and sexual dimorphism. Use the Split control to change the colored sub-group.",
    "dist_pphist": "Histogram of body mass, overlaid by species. Set a bin width in the controls.",
    "dist_ppecdf": "Empirical cumulative distribution of flipper length per species.",
    "comp_ppbar": "Mean body mass per species with standard-deviation error bars.",
    "comp_ppgrid": "Mean body mass across species (rows) by island (columns).",
    "comp_ppcats": "Parallel categories flow: species to island to sex. Pick fields with the Field selectors; color via Group By.",
    "comp_ppsun": "Counts nested by island, then species, then sex. Reorder levels with the Level selectors; turn on Theme colors to use the Appearance palette.",
    "comp_pptree": "Same hierarchy as the sunburst shown as a treemap. Reorder levels with the Level selectors.",
    "time_pptime": "Mean body mass by year for each species (year treated as a date in this showcase).",
    "time_ppctrl": "Control chart of body mass over year with mean and +/-3 sigma limits.",
    "rel_iftdmp8p1": "We plot a scatter of Body Mass from Flipper Length. The trendline shows a positive relationship. Looking at the bottom of the page, the statistics show for Scatter/Overall Population/Flipper Length (mm)\tvs Body Mass (g)\tan R2 of\t0.759",
    "rel_4sxrgwkh2": "But our dataset include penguin species. Let's enrich this scatter matrix: let's group by species. The color of each species can be set in the left panel: \"Appearance\" tab -> \"Series Styling & Aliases\". When we set such settings, pulsating dot appears next to that collapsible group. Let's dig into the details of that Body Mass vs Flipper Length per species in the next graph.",
    "rel_41zsog56y": "Using the Scatter graph: we are showing Bill Length as a function of the Flipper Length. Grouping by Species, we can get more specific details. The \"Marginal\" checkbox displays distribution of each species for the 2 measures in box plot...Go ahead and move the mouse over the vertical and horizontal box plots on the side. Notice that the \"Relationship Analysis\" at the bottom of the page displays basic statistics for each graph in the order the graphs appear. Let's keep digging.",
    "rel_dwiz6585m": "Let's keep enriching the same graph. We can make the size of each point varying based on another variable. So instead of \"Uniform\" (the default), let's set the size to Body Mass. It's not that surprising that birds with small bill length and small flipper length are in general lighter. But let's add yet another dimension to our graph...",
    "rel_lg11e7xrr": "We add another dimension: the penguin's sex. We have set the style (see Third-Field styling\") to thick outline for N/A, normal thickness and no fill for females, and filled color points for males. We can see that male penguin are generally heavier than females",
    "rel_mskuo9fip": "Correlation heatmap (Pearson r) among the four body measurements for the visible rows...",
    "rel_lxutf9m5p": "Click on top of the right bar, keep the mouse button down and scroll down to see the properties of penguins, starting from the heavier birds.",
    "rel_x10yasmg4": "Parallel coordinates across the four measurements. Drag along any axis to brush and filter the threads live.",
    "rel_076wn8q12": "We add another dimension: the penguin's sex. We have set the style (see Third-Field styling\") to thick outline for N/A, normal thickness and no fill for females, and filled color points for males. We can see that male penguin are generally heavier than females",
    "rel_4iwb6yzwm": "We add another dimension: the penguin's sex. We have set the style (see Third-Field styling\") to thick outline for N/A, normal thickness and no fill for females, and filled color points for males. We can see that male penguin are generally heavier than females",
    "rel_0vdxes29m": "We add another dimension: the penguin's sex. We have set the style (see Third-Field styling\") to thick outline for N/A, normal thickness and no fill for females, and filled color points for males. We can see that male penguin are generally heavier than females",
    "rel_4p9gp4448": "3D scatter of bill length, bill depth and flipper length. Drag to rotate, scroll to zoom; the species sit in separate regions.",
    "rel_5181y2qq1": "3D scatter of bill length, bill depth and flipper length. Drag to rotate, scroll to zoom; the species sit in separate regions.",
    "dist_t0krirew6": "Body mass distribution per species (box plot with mean).",
    "dist_epz0f3xff": "Body mass distribution per species (box plot with mean).",
    "dist_hwg6jcw6c": "Body mass distribution per species (box plot with mean)."
  },
